    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-05-30T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-05-30T01:00:00-05:00" n="421"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d421">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.002/5–3049: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister-Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clark</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-05-30T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 30, 1949—2 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 30—5:49 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Cantel 499. Can find no confirmation press reports Generalissimo plans visit
                    Canton. On other hand, there is likelihood Li Tsung-jen wall visit Generalissimo
                    sometime prior removal capital Chungking.</p>
                <pb facs="0364" n="354" xml:id="pg_354"/>
                <p>Reshuffle Cabinet being discussed today with Chu Cheng, President Judicial Yuan,
                    likely Premier. Subordinate personnel various ministries have been asked choose
                    whether they desire accompany Government Chungking, remain Canton or proceed
                    Taiwan. Because of transportation difficulties, movement of subordinate
                    personnel has been authorized and starting. Although some may stop Chungking,
                    seems likely vast majority will either remain Canton or go Taiwan. Likelihood
                    increased therefore that when Government moves Chungking, will be façade only of
                    ministers without adequate staff.</p>
                <p>Have rumor that if Chu Cheng become[s] Premier, Wellington Koo will be appointed
                    some position UN and replaced possibly by Quo Tai-chi.<note n="51"
                        xml:id="d421fn51">Chinese Minister for Foreign Affairs in 1841.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Department, repeated Nanking 342, Shanghai 295.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
